02 Jul 2018 07:42






I think the point is that the author is an omni-present, timeless being who literally narrates the fabric of time - effectively a god. The O5 was trying to use this knowledge and break the narrative, which the author clearly didn't like.

The first addendum speaks of priests, who are clearly privy to the knowledge of the baselisk. It isn't said that they help anyone who asks for it - perhaps that man's daughter is destined to remain sick and die. Perhaps the subject's wife is doomed to be sterile, and that his pottery were going to shatter. The priests don't intervene, perhaps because they know of the danger of doing so, but at the same time are able to harmlessly speak of the future, because they can  it without doing anything to affect it.

I'd say that the author simply has the power to do whatever they want to to people who try to violate the already-written narrative.







